File and Directory Management
-----------------------------
ls               # Lists the contents of a directory.
cd               # Changes the current working directory.
pwd              # Prints the current working directory path.
mkdir            # Creates new directories.
rmdir            # Removes empty directories.
rm               # Deletes files or directories.
cp               # Copies files and directories.
mv               # Moves or renames files and directories.
touch            # Creates an empty file or updates file timestamps.
find             # Searches for files and directories based on criteria.
locate           # Quickly finds files by name using a pre-built database.
stat             # Displays detailed information about a file or filesystem.
tree             # Shows directory contents in a tree-like format.

Viewing and Editing files
-------------------------
cat              # Concatenates and displays file contents.
less             # Views file content page by page.
more             # Similar to less, but with fewer features.
head             # Displays the first few lines of a file.
tail             # Displays the last few lines of a file.
nano             # A simple text editor for quick edits.
vim              # A powerful, feature-rich text editor.
emacs            # Another extensible text editor.
grep             # Searches for patterns in files and outputs matching lines.
sed              # A stream editor for filtering and transforming text.
awk              # A programming language for pattern scanning and processing.
diff             # Compares two files line by line and shows differences.

System Information
------------------
top              # Displays dynamic real-time system resource usage.
htop             # An enhanced version of top with a user-friendly interface.
uname            # Displays system information like kernel name and version.
df               # Reports file system disk space usage.
du               # Estimates disk usage of files and directories.
free             # Displays information about memory usage.
uptime           # Shows how long the system has been running.
lscpu            # Displays information about the CPU architecture.
lsblk            # Lists block devices and their mount points.
lspci            # Lists all PCI devices.

Networking
----------
ping             # Tests network connectivity to a host.
ifconfig         # Configures network interfaces (deprecated; use ip).
ip               # Manages network interfaces and routing.
netstat          # Displays network connections, routing tables, etc.
curl             # Transfers data to or from a server.
wget             # Downloads files from the web.
ssh              # Securely connects to a remote host.
scp              # Securely copies files between hosts.
ftp              # Transfers files using the File Transfer Protocol.

User and Group Management
-------------------------
whoami           # Displays the current user ID and name.
useradd          # Creates a new user account.
usermod          # Modifies an existing user account.
userdel          # Deletes a user account.
passwd           # Changes a user's password.
groupadd         # Creates a new user group.
groupmod         # Modifies an existing group.
groupdel         # Deletes a group.

Process Management
------------------
ps               # Displays a snapshot of current processes.
top              # Shows dynamic real-time process information.
kill             # Terminates a process by its PID.
pkill            # Kills processes by name.
bg               # Places a job in the background.
fg               # Brings a job to the foreground.
jobs             # Lists active jobs in the current shell.
nice             # Starts a command with a modified scheduling priority.

Disk and File System Management
-------------------------------
mount            # Mounts a filesystem to a directory.
umount           # Unmounts a filesystem.
fsck             # Checks and repairs a Linux filesystem.
fdisk            # Manages disk partitions.
mkfs             # Creates a filesystem on a partition.
df               # Reports filesystem disk space usage.
du               # Shows disk usage of files and directories.

Archive and Compression
-----------------------
tar              # Archives files.
gzip             # Compresses files.
gunzip           # Decompresses files.
zip              # Packages and compresses files.
unzip            # Extracts compressed files from a zip archive.
bzip2            # Compresses files using the bzip2 algorithm.
tar -czf         # Creates a compressed tarball.
tar -xzf         # Extracts a compressed tarball.

Miscellaneous
-------------
echo             # Displays a line of text or variable value.
history          # Shows a list of previously executed commands.
alias            # Creates a shortcut for a command.
chmod            # Changes file permissions.
chown            # Changes file owner and group.
killall          # Kills processes by name.
hostname         # Displays or sets the system's hostname.
date             # Displays or sets the current date and time.
man              # Displays the manual pages for commands.

Package Management(Debian Based)
--------------------------------
apt update       # Updates the package index.
apt upgrade      # Upgrades installed packages to the latest versions.
apt install      # Installs a specified package.
apt remove       # Removes a specified package.
apt search       # Searches for a specified package.

Package Management(Red Hat Based)
---------------------------------
yum update       # Updates the package index.
yum install      # Installs a specified package.
yum remove       # Removes a specified package.
dnf update       # Similar to yum but with additional features.

Virtualization and Containerization
-----------------------------------
docker           # Manages containers using the Docker platform.
vagrant          # Manages virtualized environments easily.

Scripting and Automation
------------------------
bash             # The Bourne Again SHell, a popular command-line shell.
sh               # The original Bourne shell, a command interpreter.
cron             # Schedules commands to run at specified intervals.
